<subSubSection box="[264,939,964,990]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="70.[264,939,964,990]" box="[264,939,964,990]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<heading bold="true" box="[264,939,964,990]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,939,964,990]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Group of 
<taxonomicName authority="(de Saussure)" baseAuthorityName="de Saussure" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[386,939,964,990]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Mischocyttarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metathoracicus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[386,763,964,990]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Mischocyttarus metathoracicus</emphasis>
(de Saussure)
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="70.[264,1323,1039,1465]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
Species of this group have the clypeus a little less wide than others in the subgenus, and the limit between the propodeum and lower metapleuron is marked by a sulcus (shallower and less marked than in the group of 
<taxonomicName box="[717,887,1119,1145]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Mischocyttarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="injucundus">
<emphasis box="[717,741,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[759,887,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">injucundus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The propodeum is greatly inflated anteriorly and the median furrow relatively short and shallow. The metanotum is yellow as well as most of the propodeal dorsum in most cases. Of the names considered valid by 
<bibRefCitation author="Richards, O. W." box="[264,457,1239,1265]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" refId="ref62496" refString="Richards, O. W. (1978) The social wasps of the Americas excluding the Vespinae." type="book" year="1978">Richards (1978)</bibRefCitation>
, only 
<taxonomicName authority="(de Saussure)" baseAuthorityName="de Saussure" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[531,919,1239,1265]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Mischocyttarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metathoracicus">
<emphasis box="[531,555,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[571,752,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">metathoracicus</emphasis>
(de Saussure)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Zikan" authorityName="Zikan" authorityYear="1935" box="[978,1278,1239,1265]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Mischocyttarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellatus">
<emphasis box="[978,1002,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1018,1202,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">flavoscutellatus</emphasis>
Zikán
</taxonomicName>
are here maintained, and three new species are added to the group. 
<taxonomicName authority="Silveira, 2006" authorityName="Silveira" authorityYear="2006" box="[1028,1322,1279,1304]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Mischocyttarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occiduus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1028,1322,1279,1304]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Mischocyttarus occiduus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,331,1318,1344]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[264,331,1318,1344]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
shows a different color pattern on the propodeum, with smaller and not completely fused yellow spots. Its patterns of sculpture of the cuticle also seem to be stronger than in the other species. If 
<taxonomicName authority="Silveira, 2006" authorityName="Silveira" authorityYear="2006" box="[499,642,1399,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Mischocyttarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occiduus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[499,523,1399,1424]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[538,642,1399,1424]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">occiduus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[649,715,1398,1424]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[649,715,1398,1424]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is correctly assigned to this group then it is the only one known to occur west of the Andes.
</paragraph>
